```@raw html
<div class="markdown"><h1>Node Classification with Graph Neural Networks</h1><p>In this tutorial, we will be learning how to use Graph Neural Networks (GNNs) for node classification. Given the ground-truth labels of only a small subset of nodes, and want to infer the labels for all the remaining nodes (transductive learning).</p></div>


```
## Import
```@raw html
<div class="markdown">
<p>Let us start off by importing some libraries. We will be using Flux.jl and <code>GraphNeuralNetworks.jl</code> for our tutorial.</p></div>

<pre class='language-julia'><code class='language-julia'>begin
    using MLDatasets
    using GraphNeuralNetworks
    using Flux
    using Flux: onecold, onehotbatch, logitcrossentropy
    using Plots
    using PlutoUI
    using TSne
    using Random
    using Statistics

    ENV["DATADEPS_ALWAYS_ACCEPT"] = "true"
    Random.seed!(17) # for reproducibility
end;</code></pre>
```

## Dataset: Cora
```@raw html
<div class="markdown">
<p>For our tutorial, we will be using the <code>Cora</code> dataset. <code>Cora</code> is a citation network of 2708 documents classified into one of seven classes and 5429 links. Each node represent articles/documents and the edges between these nodes if one of them cite each other.</p><p>Each publication in the dataset is described by a 0/1-valued word vector indicating the absence/presence of the corresponding word from the dictionary. The dictionary consists of 1433 unique words.</p><p>This dataset was first introduced by <a href="https://arxiv.org/abs/1603.08861">Yang et al. (2016)</a> as one of the datasets of the <code>Planetoid</code> benchmark suite. We will be using <a href="https://juliaml.github.io/MLDatasets.jl/stable/">MLDatasets.jl</a> for an easy access to this dataset.</p></div>

<pre class='language-julia'><code class='language-julia'>dataset = Cora()</code></pre>

The <code>node_data</code> contains <code>features</code> indicating if certain words are present or not and <code>targets</code> indicating the class for each document. We convert the single-graph dataset to a <code>GNNGraph</code>.</p></div>

    x = g.ndata.features

    y = onehotbatch(g.ndata.targets, 1:7)
    train_mask = g.ndata.train_mask
    num_features = size(x)[1]
    hidden_channels = 16
    num_classes = dataset.metadata["num_classes"]
```

## Multi-layer Perception Network (MLP)
```@raw html
<div class="markdown">
<p>In theory, we should be able to infer the category of a document solely based on its content, <em>i.e.</em> its bag-of-words feature representation, without taking any relational information into account.</p><p>Let's verify that by constructing a simple MLP that solely operates on input node features (using shared weights across all nodes):</p></div>

<pre class='language-julia'><code class='language-julia'>begin
    struct MLP
        layers::NamedTuple
    end

    Flux.@layer :expand MLP

    function MLP(num_features, num_classes, hidden_channels; drop_rate = 0.5)
        layers = (hidden = Dense(num_features =&gt; hidden_channels),
                  drop = Dropout(drop_rate),
                  classifier = Dense(hidden_channels =&gt; num_classes))
        return MLP(layers)
    end

    function (model::MLP)(x::AbstractMatrix)
        l = model.layers
        x = l.hidden(x)
        x = relu(x)
        x = l.drop(x)
        x = l.classifier(x)
        return x
    end
end</code></pre>



<div class="markdown"><h3>Training a Multilayer Perceptron</h3><p>Our MLP is defined by two linear layers and enhanced by <a href="https://fluxml.ai/Flux.jl/stable/models/nnlib/#NNlib.relu">ReLU</a> non-linearity and <a href="https://fluxml.ai/Flux.jl/stable/models/layers/#Flux.Dropout">Dropout</a>. Here, we first reduce the 1433-dimensional feature vector to a low-dimensional embedding (<code>hidden_channels=16</code>), while the second linear layer acts as a classifier that should map each low-dimensional node embedding to one of the 7 classes.</p><p>Let's train our simple MLP by following a similar procedure as described in <a href="https://carlolucibello.github.io/GraphNeuralNetworks.jl/dev/tutorials/introductory_tutorials/gnn_intro_pluto/#Hands-on-introduction-to-Graph-Neural-Networks">the first part of this tutorial</a>. We again make use of the <strong>cross entropy loss</strong> and <strong>Adam optimizer</strong>. This time, we also define a <strong><code>accuracy</code> function</strong> to evaluate how well our final model performs on the test node set (which labels have not been observed during training).</p></div>

<pre class='language-julia'><code class='language-julia'>function train(model::MLP, data::AbstractMatrix, epochs::Int, opt)
    Flux.trainmode!(model)

    for epoch in 1:epochs
        loss, grad = Flux.withgradient(model) do model
            ŷ = model(data)
            logitcrossentropy(ŷ[:, train_mask], y[:, train_mask])
        end

        Flux.update!(opt, model, grad[1])
        if epoch % 200 == 0
            @show epoch, loss
        end
    end
end</code></pre>
<pre class="code-output documenter-example-output" id="var-train">train (generic function with 1 method)</pre>

<pre class='language-julia'><code class='language-julia'>function accuracy(model::MLP, x::AbstractMatrix, y::Flux.OneHotArray, mask::BitVector)
    Flux.testmode!(model)
    mean(onecold(model(x))[mask] .== onecold(y)[mask])
end</code></pre>
<pre class="code-output documenter-example-output" id="var-accuracy">accuracy (generic function with 1 method)</pre>

<pre class='language-julia'><code class='language-julia'>begin
    mlp = MLP(num_features, num_classes, hidden_channels)
    opt_mlp = Flux.setup(Adam(1e-3), mlp)
    epochs = 2000
    train(mlp, g.ndata.features, epochs, opt_mlp)
end</code></pre>



<div class="markdown"><p>After training the model, we can call the <code>accuracy</code> function to see how well our model performs on unseen labels. Here, we are interested in the accuracy of the model, <em>i.e.</em>, the ratio of correctly classified nodes:</p></div>

<pre class='language-julia'><code class='language-julia'>accuracy(mlp, g.ndata.features, y, .!train_mask)</code></pre>
<pre class="code-output documenter-example-output" id="var-hash179283">0.45872274143302183</pre>


<div class="markdown"><p>As one can see, our MLP performs rather bad with only about 47% test accuracy. But why does the MLP do not perform better? The main reason for that is that this model suffers from heavy overfitting due to only having access to a <strong>small amount of training nodes</strong>, and therefore generalizes poorly to unseen node representations.</p><p>It also fails to incorporate an important bias into the model: <strong>Cited papers are very likely related to the category of a document</strong>. That is exactly where Graph Neural Networks come into play and can help to boost the performance of our model.</p></div>


```
## Training a Graph Convolutional Neural Network (GNN)
```@raw html
<div class="markdown">
<p>Following-up on <a href="https://carlolucibello.github.io/GraphNeuralNetworks.jl/dev/tutorials/introductory_tutorials/node_classification_pluto/#Multi-layer-Perception-Network-(MLP)">the first part of this tutorial</a>, we replace the <code>Dense</code> linear layers by the <a href="https://carlolucibello.github.io/GraphNeuralNetworks.jl/dev/api/conv/#GraphNeuralNetworks.GCNConv"><code>GCNConv</code></a> module. To recap, the <strong>GCN layer</strong> (<a href="https://arxiv.org/abs/1609.02907">Kipf et al. (2017)</a>) is defined as</p><p class="tex">$$\mathbf{x}_v^{(\ell + 1)} = \mathbf{W}^{(\ell + 1)} \sum_{w \in \mathcal{N}(v) \, \cup \, \{ v \}} \frac{1}{c_{w,v}} \cdot \mathbf{x}_w^{(\ell)}$$</p><p>where <span class="tex">\(\mathbf{W}^{(\ell + 1)}\)</span> denotes a trainable weight matrix of shape <code>[num_output_features, num_input_features]</code> and <span class="tex">\(c_{w,v}\)</span> refers to a fixed normalization coefficient for each edge. In contrast, a single <code>Linear</code> layer is defined as</p><p class="tex">$$\mathbf{x}_v^{(\ell + 1)} = \mathbf{W}^{(\ell + 1)} \mathbf{x}_v^{(\ell)}$$</p><p>which does not make use of neighboring node information.</p></div>

<pre class='language-julia'><code class='language-julia'>begin
    struct GCN
        layers::NamedTuple
    end

    Flux.@layer GCN # provides parameter collection, gpu movement and more

    function GCN(num_features, num_classes, hidden_channels; drop_rate = 0.5)
        layers = (conv1 = GCNConv(num_features =&gt; hidden_channels),
                  drop = Dropout(drop_rate),
                  conv2 = GCNConv(hidden_channels =&gt; num_classes))
        return GCN(layers)
    end

    function (gcn::GCN)(g::GNNGraph, x::AbstractMatrix)
        l = gcn.layers
        x = l.conv1(g, x)
        x = relu.(x)
        x = l.drop(x)
        x = l.conv2(g, x)
        return x
    end
end</code></pre>



<div class="markdown"><p>Now let's visualize the node embeddings of our <strong>untrained</strong> GCN network.</p></div>

<pre class='language-julia'><code class='language-julia'>begin
    gcn = GCN(num_features, num_classes, hidden_channels)
    h_untrained = gcn(g, x) |&gt; transpose
    visualize_tsne(h_untrained, g.ndata.targets)
end</code></pre>
<img src="data:image/svg+xml;base64,"/>


<div class="markdown"><p>We certainly can do better by training our model. The training and testing procedure is once again the same, but this time we make use of the node features <code>x</code><strong>and</strong> the graph <code>g</code> as input to our GCN model.</p></div>

<pre class='language-julia'><code class='language-julia'>function train(model::GCN, g::GNNGraph, x::AbstractMatrix, epochs::Int, opt)
    Flux.trainmode!(model)

    for epoch in 1:epochs
        loss, grad = Flux.withgradient(model) do model
            ŷ = model(g, x)
            logitcrossentropy(ŷ[:, train_mask], y[:, train_mask])
        end

        Flux.update!(opt, model, grad[1])
        if epoch % 200 == 0
            @show epoch, loss
        end
    end
end</code></pre>
<pre class="code-output documenter-example-output" id="var-train">train (generic function with 2 methods)</pre>

<pre class='language-julia'><code class='language-julia'>function accuracy(model::GCN, g::GNNGraph, x::AbstractMatrix, y::Flux.OneHotArray,
                  mask::BitVector)
    Flux.testmode!(model)
    mean(onecold(model(g, x))[mask] .== onecold(y)[mask])
end</code></pre>
<pre class="code-output documenter-example-output" id="var-accuracy">accuracy (generic function with 2 methods)</pre>

<pre class='language-julia'><code class='language-julia'>begin
    opt_gcn = Flux.setup(Adam(1e-2), gcn)
    train(gcn, g, x, epochs, opt_gcn)
end</code></pre>



<div class="markdown"><p>Now let's evaluate the loss of our trained GCN.</p></div>

<pre class='language-julia'><code class='language-julia'>with_terminal() do
    train_accuracy = accuracy(gcn, g, g.ndata.features, y, train_mask)
    test_accuracy = accuracy(gcn, g, g.ndata.features, y, .!train_mask)

    println("Train accuracy: $(train_accuracy)")
    println("Test accuracy: $(test_accuracy)")
end</code></pre>
<pre id="plutouiterminal">Train accuracy: 1.0
Test accuracy: 0.7706386292834891
</pre>


<div class="markdown"><p><strong>There it is!</strong> By simply swapping the linear layers with GNN layers, we can reach <strong>75.77% of test accuracy</strong>! This is in stark contrast to the 59% of test accuracy obtained by our MLP, indicating that relational information plays a crucial role in obtaining better performance.</p><p>We can also verify that once again by looking at the output embeddings of our trained model, which now produces a far better clustering of nodes of the same category.</p></div>

<pre class='language-julia'><code class='language-julia'>begin
    Flux.testmode!(gcn) # inference mode

    out_trained = gcn(g, x) |&gt; transpose
    visualize_tsne(out_trained, g.ndata.targets)
end</code></pre>
<img src="data:image/svg+xml;base64,"/>
```

```@raw html
<div class="markdown">
<ol><li><p>To achieve better model performance and to avoid overfitting, it is usually a good idea to select the best model based on an additional validation set. The <code>Cora</code> dataset provides a validation node set as <code>g.ndata.val_mask</code>, but we haven't used it yet. Can you modify the code to select and test the model with the highest validation performance? This should bring test performance to <strong>82% accuracy</strong>.</p></li><li><p>How does <code>GCN</code> behave when increasing the hidden feature dimensionality or the number of layers? What happens if you swap out all <code>GCNConv</code> instances with <a href="https://carlolucibello.github.io/GraphNeuralNetworks.jl/dev/api/conv/#GraphNeuralNetworks.GATConv"><code>GATConv</code></a> layers that make use of attention? Try to write a 2-layer <code>GAT</code> model that makes use of 8 attention heads in the first layer and 1 attention head in the second layer, uses a <code>dropout</code> ratio of <code>0.6</code> inside and outside each <code>GATConv</code> call, and uses a <code>hidden_channels</code> dimensions of <code>8</code> per head.</p></li></ol></div>
```
